I'm just whinging about how badly the API has been designed. so the issue is that when a statement doesn't require variable substitutions, it should be possible to invoke executeSql() by providing just a SQL statement and a callback, without having to also specify an empty array in between. so maybe if the variable substituion step was somehow separated from the executeSql call 6d05f0c2942adc25946a4b02b37ffa00, from experince, I know how much it sucks to have to remember to write the null in the middle of executeSql("SELECT * FROM t", null, callback) 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, I know, that's the problem 6d05f0c2942adc25946a4b02b37ffa00, the problem is, once we've shipped and developers start using it, it's too late to fix problems like this 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, our developer said he's not comfortable with making the arguments parameter optional but he's fixed our implementation so that at least we get a more meaningful error message than before 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, also, can you make the webdatabase spec clearer in step 10 of the processing model, where it says: ok, will do

69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I have (non-online) tests for missing arguments, which seem to cover that case - FF3/O9.5 throw an exception (of the wrong type), S3 throws an exception for <= 2 arc arguments and executes the command for >= 3, so it's just Safari's problem About the case where the arc is larger than 2pi? Okay I think just the second sentence is new, to handle the cases where the arc is wound around more than 2pi (by making those cases draw the entire circle, rather than making the arc jump back to zero length when the angle difference exceeds 2pi) needs to work out a better way of describing how he thinks algorithms should be tweaked to work differently I did, in my third paragraph :-) The new definition seems wrong, but I need to work out precisely how it's wrong... It's at least wrong in that it doesn't define the start and end points, if the angle difference is >=2pi tries to remember which way clocks turn I think I looked at http://www.validlab.com/754R/drafts/archive/2006-10-04.pdf via http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_754r so it might be good to double-check with a more reliable source Hmm, the spec change doesn't solve the problem I suggested in my email (since arc(x, y, r, 0, 2*pi-epsilon, true) will draw an almost-zero-length arc, and it's possible that 2*Math.PI == 2*pi-epsilon), but neither does the solution I suggested, and actually I'm not sure any decent solution is possible At least with the new spec you can write arc(x, y, r, 0, 2*Math.PI, false) and be sure it's going to draw a circle, which wasn't possible before now so I think that should be alright I'm sure I came to a different conclusion when I last thought about this, but now when I draw lots of little arcs I can't work out any way it could work sensibly in all cases so the spec sounds as sensible as it could be though not as compatible with existing implementations as it could be If it said "if anticlockwise and start-end > 2pi, or if clockwise and end-start > 2pi", instead of "if abs(start-end) > 2pi", then it would match the behaviour of Firefox and Safari They draw the arc from (start mod 2pi) anticlockwise to (end mod 2pi) Firefox and Safari will need to be changed to match the spec anyway, because they handle arc(x,y,r, 0, 4*Math.PI, false) by drawing a 4pi arc (which is kind of crazy) instead of a 2pi arc, so I suppose it doesn't hurt if the spec requires some extra changes too They don't do something different for 0..2pi+e than for -(2pi+e)..0 since that's just uniformly rotating the whole arc by -(2pi+e) The issue is that for 0..3pi clockwise they draw a circle, and for 0..3pi anticlockwise they draw a semicircle That doesn't make more or less sense to me than any other thing the spec could require - it just has the advantage of matching most deployed implementations The most sensible solution would be "if clockwise and end < start, or if anticlockwise and end > start, throw an exception because you're being silly and trying to draw the arc in the wrong direction" Actually you could just skip the clockwise/anticlockwise flag entirely, and have it depend solely on the relative angles But that doesn't work so well for compatibility with existing code/implementations notices that he has trouble thinking coherently, and goes to bed

fair enough don't they use other people's traffic as cover traffic? i mean it's not as good as a continuous stream, but... wow, interesting i'm sure timing for example, if a site sends a ping every 2s in one mode and a ping every 2.5s in another mode, even if they're the same size, you can tell which mode the app is in just by looking at when the packets are sent the general topic here is called "side channel attacks". q.v. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Side_channel_attack power consumption is another one that that page mentions e.g. you can tell what's going on based on how much power you are pulling -- if it's just idling, it'll use less power than if it's doing heavy computation also in the case of TLS communication on the web there's things like DNS requests, the IP address of the communication's destination, etc e.g. you can tell if someone is logging in on big sites because they get redirected through a separate login service even if the data is mixed in with noise like i was suggesting earlier, you can also learn things by watching what happens if you flip random bits in the stream since the receiving end might just discard the noise rather than verify that it wasn't tampered with (encryption typically avoids this, q.v. integrity) encryption systems, i should say encryption itself doesn't

is the semicolon at the end of a sql statement part of the sql statement? what i really want to know is what are people going to implement? yeah but sqlite seems to do it differently need is one thing; i'm worried about allow <div> is gonna be a pain i really don't want <body><div>test</div></body> to be conforming (or <body><div><img ...></div></body>) but people are having issues with my suggestion of <form><p>...</p><p>...</p></form> instead of <form><div>...</div><div>...</div></form> (where ... = <label> ... </label>) i think it makes a difference, but i conveniently have to sleep now and can't defend my position. :-) nn

Most SQL APIs only accept a single statement-like-thing with no semicolon, so I assume the actual statement doesn't include a semicolon (and it's handled by command-line UIs instead), but that's not very helpful if you want to be precise about what SQL calls a statement http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/c-api-multiple-queries.html talks about statements "separated" by semicolons (though only when you turn on an appropriate flag), so they're separators rather than terminators in that kind of API http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/mysql-stmt-prepare.html - "You should not add a terminating semicolon (;) or \g to the statement." sqlite3_complete is the only thing that the documentation says cares about semicolons, and that's just designed for command-line input - I'm fairly sure the rest of the API doesn't need semicolons (unless that's being hidden by all the language bindings I've used) (I vaguely think different systems differ in whether a trailing semicolon is ignored or a syntax error, but can't really remember) no longer thinks about block vs inline when writing HTML because it's just a waste of time and makes no practical difference, and would like it if conformance checkers didn't complain about that, but maybe that's just laziness :-)

5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0, why not?  That's what data-* is meant for. Man, Scalia writes awesome opinions.  http://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/10pdf/08-1448.pdf Cogent and extremely sarcastic. "One study, for example, found that children who had just finished playing violent video games were more likely to fill in the blank letter in explo_e with a d (so that it  reads explode) than with an r (explore).  App. 496, 506  (internal quotation marks omitted). The prevention of this phenomenon,  which  might have been anticipated with common sense, is not a compelling state interest." Scalia's decisions are always like that. Roberts is good too. I think Alito's concurrence makes sense too. But then, I think court interpretations of the First Amendment can be kind of extreme sometimes. Why shouldn't they have them?  They're basically just collections of people.  Your right to free speech shouldn't be affected by who you're being paid by. You can imprison individual people who individually did things wrong.  Corporations don't have volition, they only have assets.  They're controlled entirely by individual people. They don't.  The people they employ do. Or rather, the rights that have are corollaries of the rights of their employees. People who run ads or lobby Congress on behalf of a corporation aren't any less entitled to do so than people who do so on behalf of individuals or themselves. Just because you were told to do it by a manager in exchange for a paycheck from a corporate bank account doesn't mean you have any less right to do it. Of course they aren't.  But they can pay you to exercise your right of political speech on their behalf.  That's all corporations can ever do -- they can't talk or write anything *themselves*.  They're legal fictions.  Any speech is necessarily speech by some person. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, constitutional rights in America are generally viewed as unalienable, not as being granted in exchange for fulfilling responsibilities. Convicted murderers spending a life sentence in prison still have the same right to free speech as anyone. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, well, corporations basically only have assets.  When it comes to the disposition of those assets, they have similar responsibilities to individuals, often much greater responsibilities (depending on the type of corporation).  That is, they can be held fiscally liable for breaking the law.  But if it's anything non-monetary, you can't really take actions against a corporation, you have to take action against the individuals responsible. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, that's orthogonal to the question of corporations.  "Corporation" doesn't mean "big business", it means an entity that can legally act as a person in some respects.  Small charities and whatever are also often incorporated. It's not the corporation that's shielding anything, it's the money and influence.  Corporations are designed to be a good vehicle for concentrating arbitrarily large amounts of money, so it just so happens that any organization of note is going to be incorporated. That's not the fault of the incorporation. If incorporation didn't exist, you'd see the same thing with large private businesses. It's simpler than that, it's just that large businesses are powerful enough to have bargaining power with the government. In many cases they can credibly threaten the government. For instance, a big business could threaten to leave a particular state if it's taxed too heavily. That could cause thousands of people to lose their jobs, which would create a big backlash by the general public against the politicians in power. 5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0, well, yes, that's how capitalism works.  In a capitalist society, it's very easy to start businesses, because investors have the promise of exorbitant returns. Most large companies don't pay dividends, though. And if they do, it's only a very small fraction of profit, like one or two percent. So it's not a big deal in the scheme of things. Right, and dividends slow down the company's growth sometimes. 5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0, hostile takeovers of that sort are very rare.  A publicly-traded company almost always has far higher market capitalization than assets.  Usually when you have that sort of systematic buy-out, it's an attempt to merge one company into a larger one or such. But it's hard to pull off, because trying it causes the stock price to shoot up. Anyway, if you do buy a lot of stock in the company, it's rarely in your interest to try grabbing the assets and running.  You want to hold onto the stock and let it go up in price, then sell it.  That almost always provides better returns. Except if the company's stock price has really crashed, then it's sometimes worthwhile to buy it just for the sake of liquidating it. 5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0, practically any economic activity causes externalities, both positive and negative.  Big businesses can bring a lot of positive economic effects, like greatly reduced costs through economy of scale. They can devote a much larger amount of their budget to R&D and innovation, etc. Well, yes, but you can't fairly complain about the negative externalities unless you have evidence that they outweigh the positive externalities.

Topic: Review and tweak agenda AB: the draft agenda was posted yesterday ( http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-webapps/2010JulSep/0447.html ). The two specs on the agenda are Widget Interface and the Widget URI scheme. Any change requests? RT: I would like to talk about Widget Updates spec AB: ok, will add that to the end of the meeting Topic: Announcements AB: any short announcements today? Topic: TWI spec: Action-568 AB: earlier this week discussion on openURL removal continued ( http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-webapps/2010JulSep/0394.html ) AB: Bryan Sullivan had some comments ... I was hoping Bryan would join today but he hasn't AB: I believe Marcos position is very clear ... he wants it removed from the spec RB: as far as I am concerned, agree it is useful ... but it is also problematic ... Think it should be solved somewhere else RT: yes, there is a complexity issue here ... so I agree with Marcos and Robin RB: if we remove it, we should be able to go straight to REC AB: we could go to PR but not REC because of some dependency issues RB: dependency on HTML5? AB: yes that is one AB: I also tend to agree with the arguments to remove the functionality ... and defer to some other spec for equivalent functionality AB: I'll start an explict CfC about removing this method from the spec ... I'd like to make sure everyone has an opportunity to state their position ACTION: barstow start a CfC about openURL and Action-568 AB: anything else on that topic for today? [ No ] Topic: URI Scheme spec AB: it has been a while since we discussed the widget: scheme spec ( http://dev.w3.org/cvsweb/2006/waf/widgets-uri/ ) AB: what's the status and plan? RB: I still need to address some issues ... I plan to make it a priority ... hope to finish by the end of the month ... I know the action items AB: ok, great AB: does anyone have any implementation status for this spec? RB: I found it easy to implement AB: the spec says authors shouldn't use this scheme ... so what's the use case RB: when using the DOM, need to determine an absolute URI ... so impls need it ... it could also to lead to security hole if an implementor was to use something like a file: URI ... at runtime it is needed ... e.g. to reuse a web runtime engine AB: anything else on that spec? RT: we use it for some projects ... good to get rid of the file: issue Topic: Widget Updates spec RT: I've been working with Marcos on this spec ... clarified update description ... started an alogorithm to do the update ... would like to get some feedback AB: I haven't looked at the changes RB: same here although I will do so shortly RT: addresses comparing signatures for the installed widget and the update widget ... so please do take a look AB: to get broader review, it often helps to publish a new version AB: when will it be ready for a new pub? RT: I have another couple of weeks of work to do before it is ready AB: ok, that sounds good AB: perhaps we can put it on the agenda for the next call which is probably in 2 weeks RT: any feedback now would be good AB: I'll ask for internal review AB: are there some existing protocols this functionality could be layered on? ... e.g. the DM stuff from OMA RT: yes, there is some existing work to consider ... if you have related feedback, that would be useful AB: anything else on Updates spec for today? RT: not from me Topic: AoB AB: anything else for today? AB: the bulk of the remaining work for the widget specs is test cases ... and it is great to see that Opera is contributing in that area ... e.g. DigSig tests and WARP tests AB: next call will be August 26 if there is something to discuss otherwise, September 2 AB: let's continue to use public-webapps so that we can eliminate and/or shorten our voice conferences AB: meeting adjourned RRSAgent, make minutes
